Figures 11-16
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="83" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="83" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
Compared to the most closely related 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Cochliopidae" genus="Pyrgophorus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pyrgophorus coronatus" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="coronatus">Pyrgophorus coronatus</taxonomicName>
(L. Pfeiffer, 1840), found in other cenotes and surface waters of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Yucatán">Yucatan</normalizedToken>
(Figs 17-19), the new species differs by its smaller and more pyramidal shell shape with blunter apex and finer surface sculpture, whitish periorostracum, flat protoconch and less numerous whorls, more opened umbilicus, smaller and more numerous nodules and different shape of the aperture with a characteristic sinuation at its columellar edge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
Type locality. Mexico, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Yucatán">Yucatan</normalizedToken>
state, Cenotillo Municipality, Cenote Xoch, at 46 m deep by SCUBA, buried in cave sediments, 
<geoCoordinate direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="1" value="20.997564">20,997565°N</geoCoordinate>
; 
<geoCoordinate direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="1" value="-87.93666">87,936659°W</geoCoordinate>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
